== Kuroda Disturbance (黒田騒動) ==

The '''Kuroda Disturbance''' (黒田騒動, Kuroda Sōdō), also known as the '''Kuriyama Daizen Incident''' (栗山大膳事件), was an {{ill|O-Ie Sōdō|ja|お家騒動|qq=draft}} (internal clan conflict) that occurred in the {{ill|Fukuoka Domain|ja|福岡藩|qq=draft}} during the early {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft}}. It is considered one of the three major clan disputes alongside the {{ill|Date Disturbance|ja|伊達騒動|qq=draft}} and the {{ill|Kaga Disturbance|ja|加賀騒動|qq=draft}}. Unlike other conflicts of this nature, the Kuroda Disturbance resulted in no fatalities, though punishments such as confinement were imposed.

== Background ==

{{ill|Kuroda Nagamasa|ja|黒田長政|qq=draft}}, fearing the reckless nature of his eldest son {{ill|Kuroda Tadayuki|ja|黒田忠之|qq=draft}}, decided to pass leadership of the clan to his third son, {{ill|Kuroda Nagaoki|ja|黒田長興|qq=draft}}. He sent a stern letter to Tadayuki, offering harsh choices: to become a farmer with 2,000 koku of land, a merchant in Kansai with 10,000 ryō, or a monk with a stipend of 1,000 koku. 

Tadayuki's guardian, {{ill|Kuriyama Toshiaki|ja|栗山利章|qq=draft}} (known as Daizen), advised him to commit seppuku if he felt dishonored. Kuriyama gathered the heirs of samurai holding between 600 and 2,000 koku, securing a blood oath to commit seppuku unless the disinheritance was revoked. This compelled Nagamasa to relent, appointing Daizen as Tadayuki's guardian before his death.

However, tensions grew between Daizen and Tadayuki, especially after Daizen sent a letter with paternal advice that Tadayuki found patronizing. Upon becoming lord in 1624, Tadayuki favored {{ill|Kurahachi Totaifu|ja|倉八十太夫|qq=draft}} as his close advisor, granting him a large stipend and commissioning extravagant projects, such as building the opulent ship "Hōōmaru" and hiring 200 new foot soldiers—actions viewed as reckless during an era of military downsizing.

== The Conflict ==

By 1632, Daizen accused Tadayuki of plotting against the Tokugawa shogunate. The domain claimed Daizen was mentally unstable. In 1633, {{ill|Tokugawa Iemitsu|ja|徳川家光|qq=draft}} personally adjudicated the case, siding with Tadayuki and affirming the clan's holdings, thus ending a decade-long conflict.

Daizen was placed under house arrest in {{ill|Morioka Domain|ja|盛岡藩|qq=draft}}, and Kurahachi was exiled to {{ill|Mount Kōya|ja|高野山|qq=draft}}. Kurahachi later died in the Kansai region, with his family only regaining samurai status generations later.

== Cultural Depictions ==

The Kuroda Disturbance inspired numerous {{ill|kabuki|ja|歌舞伎|qq=draft}} plays during the Edo period, including "{{ill|Otogibanashi Hakata Ori|ja|御伽譚博多新織|qq=draft}}" by {{ill|Segawa Jokō|ja|瀬川如皐|qq=draft}} and "{{ill|Kokuhaku Oriwakemono Hakata|ja|黒白論織分博多|qq=draft}}" by {{ill|Kawatake Mokuami|ja|河竹黙阿弥|qq=draft}}. The longest {{ill|gōkan|ja|合巻|qq=draft}} novel, "{{ill|Shiranui Monogatari|ja|しらぬひ譚|qq=draft}}", also dramatized the event.

In modern literature, {{ill|Mori Ōgai|ja|森鷗外|qq=draft}} fictionalized the incident in "{{ill|Kuriyama Daizen|ja|栗山大膳|qq=draft}}", portraying Daizen as a tragic figure striving to protect the Kuroda clan. {{ill|Takiguchi Yasuhiko|ja|滝口康彦|qq=draft}}'s "Shuka Horobubeshi" presents Daizen as a rigid, self-righteous loyalist.

The story was adapted into the 1956 film "{{ill|Kuroda Disturbance (1956 film)|ja|黒田騒動 (1956th year の映画)|qq=draft}}" directed by {{ill|Uchida Tomu|ja|内田吐夢|qq=draft}}, starring {{ill|Kataoka Chiezō|ja|片岡千恵蔵|qq=draft}} as Daizen.

